      intermediate:
        "The Cloud belongs to the apophatic (negative) theological tradition: knowing God by what God is NOT, rather than what God IS. This tradition runs from Pseudo-Dionysius (5th-6th century) through Meister Eckhart, John of the Cross, the anonymous author of the Cloud, and into modern contemplative practice.\n\nThe author's method anticipates what Thomas Keating (20th century) would formalize as 'Centering Prayer': choose a sacred word, sit in silence, return to the word when thoughts arise. The Cloud is essentially the medieval manual for what became the contemplative prayer revival of the 1970s-present.\n\nKey concepts: The 'cloud of unknowing' above you (between you and God) and the 'cloud of forgetting' below you (between you and your thoughts). The distinction between 'special' calling (contemplative prayer is not for everyone at every stage) and the universality of God's love. The insistence that this prayer is 'work' -- not passive floating but active, sustained attention.\n\nThe author is also refreshingly practical. He warns against physical postures (do not strain your body), emotional experiences (do not chase feelings), and spiritual pride (do not think contemplative prayer makes you better than other Christians). He has a sense of humor: at one point he tells the reader that if they fall asleep during prayer, it just means they needed sleep.",
